  "shareUrn": "urn:li:share:7449846609171111936",
  "text": "🔥 BREAKING: On the back of our \"Jagged Frontier\" blog post last week, we built \"nano-analyzer\" - a simple zero-day scanner (one Python file, one dependency, no agentic loop beyond simple grep) - and ran it on FreeBSD, OpenBSD, and OpenSSL, with some of the cheapest models available. \n\nThis time, no hints - the models received entire source files with no guidance on where to look. \n\nIt surfaced the same FreeBSD vulnerability (CVE-2026-4747) that Anthropic highlighted as a flagship Mythos result, multiple kernel bug candidates across FreeBSD and OpenBSD including a new bug now confirmed by the maintainer, and several additional findings under active investigation. A responsibly disclosed FreeBSD networking issue (AISLE-2026-E445) appears to have been in the codebase for over 20 years. \n\nPerhaps most striking: an open-weights model with just 5.1B active parameters independently surfaced the Mythos flagship vulnerability and multiple additional bug candidates - at 600x lower cost per token. \n\n💥 We're open-sourcing the entire analyzer codebase today.💥\n\nModels happily provided by our friends at Hugging Face (cheers Clem Delangue 🤗, Thomas Wolf, Julien Chaumond 👋)\n\nExcited to be building this with Stanislav Fort and Jaya Baloo\n\nMore details in the first comment.\n\nLET'S GO AISLE™! 🚀",
