    {
      "time": 1776409536117,
      "link": "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7449846611876405248?commentUrn=urn%3Ali%3Acomment%3A%28activity%3A7449846611876405248%2C7450801622970118144%29&dashCommentUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afsd_comment%3A%287450801622970118144%2Curn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7449846611876405248%29",
      "text": "Still apples to bananas. A single-file scanner with grep, preloaded C/C++ bug archetypes, limited bug classes, no real stateful reasoning, and permissive triage is not measuring agentic Mythos-like capability, or even agentic Opus 4.6 capability. It is measuring how well cheap models can mine shallow, local bug patterns once the task has been reduced to file-level search.\nOne such pass will predictably surface some low-hanging fruit on targets like FreeBSD/OpenBSD, then you are largely done. Useful sometimes, sure, but that is not the hard part. Actual mining for hard-to-spot bugs on hardened surfaces is much more complex: cross-file reasoning, stateful logic, exploitability assessment, and reliable verification.\nOpenSSL is the more meaningful target here, and even there the question is not \"did it emit a CVE-shaped artifact?\" but \"did it find something nontrivial, high-impact, and independently verifiable?\"\nRaw bug count/CVE count is a bad scoreboard. Weak systems mostly find weak bugs. The real benchmark is whether you can find, verify, and prioritize the bugs that older tooling and smaller models systematically miss.",
